At least 100 burrows were located on the NE slope of South (Elephant) Rock on 3/13/67. The burrows were well spaced, scattered in the short grass. This species may nest on the other islands were conditions provide a suitable habitat.

About 150 adults were on Table Rock on 4/23/67. 50-60 were noted there on 3/18/67.

Approx. 225 were observed scattered over the SE part of North Rock (North Coquille Point Rock).
Total petrel population on the rock was estimated to be between 426 and 502 individuals.  Burrows were checked in several locations but none contained birds.
12 nests were located along a ledge on the S side. 4 eggs were the maximum complement.
At least 32 nests are located on the rock. 2 nests were found on the WNW face; at least 30 nests were observed on the steep NW face just below the summit.
19 nests were located. 2 colonies were found on the NW slope (8 nests at the westerly location; 5 nests at the easterly location). 6 nests were located on the SE slope.

About 900 adult gulls were on the rock. On the basis of counts from Goat Island (5/14/66), about 80% of the 900 individuals would be employed birds (resulting) in a breeding population of (approximately) 700 birds.
49 individuals were counted. Many were noted flying to and from rock crevices.

In Table 2, transposed this colony with Haystack Rock of Clatsop Co. 4 areas are utilized by this species. Approx. 130 burrows found. NW face: est. 40 burrows.  S slope: 10 burrows counted. WNW slope: approx. 70 burrows. 50 burrows just NE of WNW slope.

69 burrows were found. An undetermined number are on NW face. 1 burrow located at bottom of ledge on S side. 47 burrows on WNW slope below CAAU colony. 18 burrows NE of the CAAU colony. 3 burrows were found on E side.

Rodents present on island. 2 burrows found on S slope of Conical Rock (Blast Rock) near its W end. Both burrows had been freshly dug; 1 burrow was checked and contained an adult. This species possibly breeds on Parrot Rock.
6 nests were found along the cliffs just S of Heceta Head Lighthouse on the mainland. These cliffs are about 60' high. Nests were located between 25-40' from the cliff face.
Adults were observed on both rocks but probably only nest on Parrot Rock (243-030). 50-60 adults were noted either on or near Parrot Rock.
12 birds were observed on Parrot Rock (243-030) and appeared to be involved in breeding activities.

13 burrows (based on adults sunning at burrow entrances or what appeared to be burrow entrances) were counted on the SE slope of Parrot Rock. This species or evidence of were not found on Conical Rock (243-029).
No sign of breeding bird activity was noted. 4 BLOY were observed feeding on W point.

3.2 ac of tall grass (Phalaris) is used by LHSP. Burrow densities were sampled and found comparable to that of Goat Island in 1966 (1.5 birds/sq. ft). Based on density factor, breeding population was estimated to be 224088 individuals.

1 pair found on NW corner of rock. Burrow on margin of LHSP colony and surrounded by 4 TUPU burrows. The pair together in burrow during day and night. At night, burrow was only one found to contain FTSP. Undoubtedly, other FTSP nest on island.

4 areas used by CAAU. 4 burrows on NW corner; 3 burrows on NE slope at edge of tall grass; 5 burrows on E side S of landing site; 5 burrows about 50 ft to S facing E on 70 degree slope. Total of 17 burrows located. CAAU were heard during night.

13 burrows found. 7 burrows on NW corner; 4 burrows just below tall grass along W margin of LHSP colony. 1 burrow showing no recent use near S end of island; 1 burrow S of landing site in tall grass adjacent to 5 CAAU burrows.
1 pair of cormorants was observed on the N side. No other bird species or signs of them were observed.

1.85 ac used by LHSP. 1.68 ac of Phalaris with density factor of 1.3 birds/sq. ft (est. 90605 individuals). 0.25 ac of short grass/unid broadleaf species with density factor of 1.0 birds/sq. ft (est. 10890 individuals). Total est. at 101495 individuals.
No UNCO observed on rock; 1 apparently finished nest was found on SSE side on 3/22/67. Signs indicated that other nests had been located in this area in past seasons.
About 35-40 adults were on rock both survey dates. Breeding activity too low to obtain accurate count of breeding population. 4 nests had been started on W slope 3/22/67.

26 CAAU burrows located near margin of tall grass on WNW slope. 1 burrow excavated to substantiate measurements. Clumps of iris and Phalaris in this area are used as burrow entrance support and cover. All burrows showed recent use.
5 burrows located in and around CAAU colony on WNW slope. 2 suspected TUPU burrows located on edge of tall grass on its SE margin. All burrows showed recent use.
1.1 ac used by LHSP. LHSP density found to be 1.0 birds/sq. ft resulting in breeding population estimate of 47916 birds on survey date.

At least 300 individuals of this species (COMU) were on a small rock N of Island Rock. We feel that the above figure is relatively conservative.

26 individuals counted. Nests observed on ESE side of rock; complete nest count could not be satisfactorily made due to steep slope. The number of nests located suggests that the breeding popl. is higher than our bird count indicates. No eggs observed.
6 individuals were observed flying from probable nest sites near the N end of the rock.
Relatively few nest depressions were located. About 300-350 adult gulls were on the rock.
Approx. 1180 birds were on the rock. 106 on the S end; 125 on the SW side; 750 on WNW side; 200 on E side. No eggs were observed. We feel that the above figures are relatively conservative.
36 individuals were counted. Many were noted flying to and from rock crevices. Undoubtedly, this species is more numerous than our figures indicate.

2 areas utilized. S area (2 burrows) is located on relatively low relief. S-most burrow contained adult with egg. This burrow was under root system of unid. rush sp. 2nd breeding area = 31 burrows and slopes seaward. Slope heavily vegetated.
13 burrows found; 11 located on the NW slope in sparse to no vegetation. All appeared to have recent use; birds observed departing and arriving at many of the burrows.
14 roosting on W side, minimum 69 roosting on E side. Estimate 175 pairs present.
2 burrows found near top of NE side (1 near-fledging age young, 1 adult on egg); no other burrow seen. Therefore, must be less than 50 pairs present.

On 3/25, 116 TUPU sized burrows counted on N slope. On 5/14, 2 sample counts of these burrows showed a 65% occupancy (116 x 0.65=75). Many TUPU observed carrying nesting material.
